			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Rooting is helpful in situations where you get adds and you can use root as a form of crowd control.  Snare should be used to make sure a mob does not run away at the end of a fight.  Here is what happens when you use each:
<br />

<br />
Root:
<br />
         The mob will not be able to move at all during the course of the whole fight, however, rather than attacking the person who has the most aggro, a rooted mob will attack the person closest to it.  That means if you were closer to the mob than the tank you would get hit.  This jeopardizes a tanks ability to hold aggro, therefore root is not particularly useful in this situation.  In addition to this, rather than running away when it reaches a certain hp%, the mob will stay and continue to fight until its death, making it that much harder of a fight.
<br />

<br />
Snare:
<br />
         The mob will be able to move during the fight but at a very slow rate that will give the tank extra time to try to take aggro back.  Rather than running away after reaching a certain hp% or staying to fight as if it were rooted, a snared mob will simply turn away and stop attacking anybody while remaining still.  So snaring would be essential in this situation because it does not jeopardize aggro but it does keep the mob from running away.
<br />

<br />
Again, you should snare each mob that your group pulls to keep it running away at the end of each fight, while you should use root to park adds so your group can focus on one mob at a time.  Hope that helps.<br />_________________<br /><img src="http://cabilis.net/Raingesignaturesharp.GIF" border="0" />
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=743326" target="_blank" class="postlink">Veteran Raine I'Ngoroth</a> - 65 Forest Stalker of Tholuxe Paells
<br />
Proud Member of <a href="http://www.kodf.com/eqdkp/viewnews.php" target="_blank" class="postlink">The Knights of Dawn Fire</a></span><span class="gentblsmall"></span></td>
